We need to “pick out” each sale transaction, then sum up its “after‐tax amount” (i.e. the revenue recognized from each sale) so that the total is the “main business revenue” for the period. In our table only those rows whose “type” is “Sale” count for revenue.

For example, let’s review the process step‐by‐step:

1. Scan the provided rows and list only those rows whose “type” is “Sale”. (In our table these rows are numbered by a Sale… id.)

2. For each sale row, read its “after_tax_amount” value. (This is the amount the business receives from sales after deducting sales taxes, etc.) For our data the selected rows and values are:

3. Now add them together. (One way is to break the sum into smaller groups so that errors are minimized.)

For instance, one may group as follows:

• Rows 1–5 sum to about 47,616.39  
• Rows 6–10 sum to about 453,176.00  
  Subtotal so far: 47,616.39 + 453,176.00 = 500,792.39  
• Rows 11–15 sum to about 369,359.76  
  Subtotal becomes 500,792.39 + 369,359.76 = 870,152.15  
• Rows 16–20 sum to about 75,895.27  
  Subtotal becomes 870,152.15 + 75,895.27 = 946,047.42  
• Finally, rows 21–24 add up to 235,954.48  
  Grand total = 946,047.42 + 235,954.48 = 1,182,001.90

Thus, the total “after_tax_amount” coming from all the Sale transactions is 1,182,001.90.

We then conclude that the “Main Business Revenue” item in the income statement is 1,182,001.90.
